section.p:
The conjugateconjugate of a complex number of the complex number z=x+iy=r\expi(\theta), denoted \overline{z}\overline{z}
conjugate of the complex number z
or z^\ast{z}^\ast
conjugate of the complex number z
, is defined to be z^\ast = x-iy = r\expi(-\theta). Geometrically, z^\ast is the reflection of z across the real axis (the x-axis) in \R^2. Here are some relations involving conjugates. For all z,w\in \C, we have the following.
\re(z) \amp = \frac{z + z^\ast}{2}
\im(z) \amp = \frac{z - z^\ast}{2i}
|z|^2 \amp = zz^\ast 2\arg z \amp = \frac{z}{z^\ast} \;\;(\text{for } z\neq 0) \frac{1}{z} \amp = \frac{z^\ast}{zz^\ast}= \frac{z^\ast}{|z|^2} \;\;(\text{for } z\neq 0) (zw)^\ast \amp = z^\ast w^\ast

statement.p:
Express each of the following in rectangular and
      polar form.


 \displaystyle \frac{2+i}{3-i}

 \displaystyle \frac{1+2i}{1-2i}

 \displaystyle \frac{2\expi({\pi/4})}{3\expi({-\pi/2})}

ol.li:
Let T(a,b) denote the
	matrix \twotwo{a}{b}{-b}{a} in {\mathcal M}_\C.
	We have the following.

	  T(a,b)+T(c,d)\amp = \twotwo{a}{b}{-b}{a} + \twotwo{c}{d}{-d}{c} 

	  \amp = \twotwo{a+c}{b+d}{-b-d}{a+c}

	  \amp = T(a+c,b+d)
	  T(a,b)T(c,d)\amp = \twotwo{a}{b}{-b}{a} \twotwo{c}{d}{-d}{c} 

	  \amp =\twotwo{ac-bd}{ad+bc}{-ad-bc}{ac-bd}

	  \amp = T(ac-bd,ad+bc)
